author: @the1theonlyg248
Movie Name: Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings

Comment: People complaining about how this isn't on par with really good martial arts movies- I agree, but honestly, Marvel movies martial arts and fighting is generally reallllyyyy bad with tons of shaky cam, constant cuts, etc. You can't follow anything, impacts are cut, and the list goes on. By Marvel standards, this is a huge improvement and I'm totally excited for it. The director claimed he was mainly inspired by the Wushu from Crouching Tiger Hidden Dragon, so yes, it's supposed to be more fantasy-esque with gravity defying action. It's fine if that's not your cup of tea, but that doesn't stop it from being impressive in regards to the niche type of martial arts action film it's emulating. It's also a great stylistic choice imo for a movie that's supposed to fit into the MCU with all these crazy superhumans with powers flying around. A dude being really good at traditional kung fu just wouldn't fit in as well, or at least not be taken AS seriously. Like look at Hawk Eye and Black Widow- sure they're dope now and people love them, but back when Avengers first came out, all the memes were about how they were just average people doing weird MMA moves against aliens while superheros flew around them blasting aliens put of the sky. This wire-work type of fantasy martial arts is a great way for there to be an illusion of fantastic power, while still showing off some brilliant choreography and traditional martial arts. Additionally, they hired the lead cinematographer from the Matrix films for this movie. The Matrix was also inspired by that CTHD style of fighting to a degree and the cinematography was amazing in that film, especially with the action. So I'm hopeful we'll get a great blend of camera work and clear action. Tldr don't be so negative and consider it a huge step from Marvel in the right direction in terms of action and martial arts in their movies.
author: @rafaysyed520
Movie Name: Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings

Comment: ¬†@BarrettBaker_photos¬† I mean it's fair to be disappointed, but give them some credit. The wire work martial arts are their own genre and they do amazing work and choreography and acrobatics for that type of action. Sure it's not 80s Hong Kong action which was also amazing, but that's like comparing apples to oranges since that was meant to be more grounded in reality. This is a sci-fi/fantasy universe they're in with super powers and stuff. Having a martial artist super hero, it make sense to give him fantasy-esque martial arts to have him fit better. Crouching Tiger Hidden Dragon trailblazed this style and did it beautifully. It's meant to be different and that's fine. It's definitely a step up from Marvel's usual shakey cam, excessively cut average action where you can't tell what's going on or see any of the choreography half the time. This seems like it's mostly wide-angles, long shots, etc which is already much better for martial arts.

Comment:
I don't want to be that guy but I have to disagree. Although the stunts and choreography do look very cool most of the shots I saw seem pretty standard and basic, almost like it's a tv show. This is one of the main problems I have with MCU movies now, there is very little or no visual style to them. Cool stuff might be happening in a scene but it's not shot in a way that enhances what's happening.
A good example of this is Doctor Strange. Stuff like the city being inverted and twisted around in the mirror dimension sounds cool but it's not really shot in a way that will enhance the impact of seeing the city you used to live in literally being turned upside down. 

By no means at all am I saying don't be excited for the film, trying to take you're enjoyment of it away, or trying to troll you. I just happen to disagree with you and I thought I would explain why.

Comment:
¬†@RealogOnlyBrodie¬† Originally Shang Chi could fight ‚Äúreally really good‚Äù, now the character (in comics at least) has had other abilities.

According to the comics...Shang Chi is one of the greatest martial artists on Earth, having been trained possibly since birth to become the ultimate warrior. Shang Chi is skilled in various martial arts with a particular specialization in the Chinese martial arts. He has been shown defeating multiple highly skilled opponents simultaneously as well as superhumans. His great strength and chi (qi) allows him to strike with inhuman force enabling him to break through barriers such as brick, concrete and iron, withstand physical impacts almost to a superhuman degree, and ease all forms of pain and discomfort. Shang has stalemated Iron Fist in single combat, with the two martial artists portrayed as equals while Black Panther stated Shang-Chi is better than Rand.

Skilled Gymnast: He has been shown to be very well versed in gymnastics.

Peak Physical Conditioning: Shang has intensively trained his body to possess the highest level of strength, speed, stamina and endurance that a human can have without artificial enhancements. His notable include the speed and stamina to endure even the most rigorous physical training exercises, reacting fast enough to dodge gunfire and even catch weapons hurled by enemies at him and throw them right back at them.

Skilled Marksman: Shang is a master marksman able to throw ranged weapons such as shuriken (throwing stars) with pin-point accuracy.

Weapons Proficiency: Shang is highly skilled with all martial arts weaponry such as the Chinese double edged sword (jian), butterfly swords, oxtail swords, staves, and both single and double nunchaku. He has often made use of make-shift weapons as well, using metal pipes and even a tree trunk.

Nervous System Control: Shang can control his nervous system enabling him to deaden his body to physical pain, resist the effects of drugs or poisons, limit the spread of toxins in his blood stream, and even slow down his bleeding rate.

Pressure Point Locator: He can locate different pressure points on a person's body; incapacitate, paralyze, severely injure, or kill a person.

Espionage: While not focused upon as much in recent appearances, Shang has undergone training during his time with MI-6 and is familiar with many espionage tactics and methodologies.

Philosopher: Shang Chi has an extensive knowledge of Eastern philosophy.

Patient Fisher: Shang Chi is a highly skilled fisherman.

Multilingual: Shang-Chi is fluent in several languages including English, Cantonese, Mandarin and ancient Mandarin. Shang-Chi also has some knowledge of French.

Physical Strength
Shang-Chi possesses the strength level of a man his age, size and weight who engages in intensive regular exercise, Shang can lift at least twice his body weight, or 350 lbs. Through his use of chi however, Shang can temporarily increase his physical strength to an unknown amount.

author: @tantikostaman1369
Movie Name: Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings

Comment:
And both the teaser & trailer are insanely good.  Probably best trailers I have ever seen.  Most trailers are just dumbed down & incongruous clips of the film.  Most of the time from these bad trailers you cannot glean or extrapolate any type of plot or get any idea of what the film is about.  Obviously you don‚Äôt want spoilers or the plot ruined but this gives you an idea of some of the story without ruining a thing.  Everything in these trailers is insane.  The music, cinematography, choreography, etc It‚Äôs all exceptional.

Also, although Shang Chi is Chinese, you get a sense of Asian pride and culture which is rare on the big screen.  The writer & director is half-Japanese like me & he crafted an amazing story & film.  The cast is superlative & Tony Leung is mind blowing as Wen-Wu.  He is more anti-hero than villain which makes you identify and be empathetic toward him.  He is not criminal or bad for the sake of it, he is driven by grief & other forces.  Marvel really did an outstanding job.  Some are gettinf tired of all the inter-film connections & relations, but I think it‚Äôs an amazing part of the worlds & stories Marvel is weaving.  Shang Chi isn‚Äôt just a run of the mill blockbuster with eye candy martial arts & CGI; it has sublime acting, universal themes & lots of depth in the story & characters.  Marvel and the cast and crew freaking crushed it.  

The Winter Soldier & Civil War are my two favorite movies and Bucky is my favorite character.  I am still geeking out from The Falcon & the Winter Soldier.  Now Shang Chi blew my mind.  It‚Äôs right there at the top.

@Gabriel Seck Chuan Loh you‚Äôre right, I am probably not in a position to tell China what to do, but being a Westerner who values openness very highly, to see all these famous western films like Top Gun and actors like John Cena censored so they can appease a foreign government is upsetting. author: @GoogleAccount-tg9lp

Comment: @Gabriel Seck Chuan Loh those are some very good questions. Openness is very important because without acknowledging ones mistakes and flaws, it is hard to move on and improve for the better. For example America has not eliminated racism by a long shot, but because of more people‚Äôs voices being heard through free speech, socially and through the law the issue has improved. Moving on from that, a key point of western ideology is the focus on rights, which I would agree is both a good and bad thing. Good in that it stops people from being censored and tries to make sure that they will always be treated with fairness, regardless of social class or race. The problem with this is that some people become obsessed with their rights, and neglect responsibilities. So in conclusion, while the West‚Äôs emphasis on rights needs to be balanced with responsibility, I do think that freedom of speech and openness are integral regardless.

Comment: ‚Äã@Gabriel Seck Chuan Loh Why not give all your power to your leader? Well that is putting a lot of stock in one person to not screw up an entire country. That leader only has one perspective, and that may cause them to be oblivious and uncaring to the suffering of many people under their rule. This is historically seen in authoritarian regimes and dictatorships of the past like Nazi Germany, Soviet Russia, and North Korea. Human rights were ignored, and countless people were killed off. Spreading the power of the law among the people who are most affected by it gives much more perspective and empathy to the law. Think about it, if a farmer in an dictatorship wants to get more irrigation infrastructure pipelines in his area, he cannot do anything about that, except hope that the dictator will hear him. In a democracy, he can vote or introduce a bill to meet his goals. Government for the people and by the people improves quality of life for citizens.

author: @spookyman6876

Comment:
It's interesting when his father said that.Because Shang-Chi is trained in using a multitude of weapons in the comics-but not firearms.I think his father should have had him trained in using firearms,too.That's what I would have done if I were his father.It's like they say in the U.S. Marine Corps,''One Mind,Any Weapon''.

Don't get me wrong,I understand that not everyone likes guns-so given that this is the case in real life,it makes perfect sense for some fictional characters in comic books not to like guns and to refuse to use them-Batman is a great example of one such character who adamantly refuses to use firearms(although in some very rare instances in the past,the character actually has used guns).There are some characters who typically don't use them and refuse to use them who don't even really need them in the first place,too,I'll concede. But 
I think that that would have been the best approach for his father to take if he wanted to make his son into this ultimate warrior.

Train him in all of these different fighting styles and disciplines,train him in how to use different types of weapons,also make sure that he's educated,thoughtful,calculating and smart,too-then you'll have someone incredibly dangerous.
I'm going to be writing my own comics and I'll have characters who are skilled martial artists who also use guns and bladed weapons and melee weapons and I'll have martial arts characters who steadfastly refuse to use firearms.

author: @mrli3666
Movie Name: Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings

Comment:
Anyone who follows the news in Chinese language in the past 20 or so years will come to the conclusion that Jackie Chen is a selfish person who does not care about anyone else. Not his wife, not his girlfriend, not his extramarital daughter, not his co-workers, not his Hong Kong compatriots. 

Jet Li visited my university for a forum ten years ago. I saw a kind and spiritual person who thinks about the meaning of life, what is good, why is there suffering in the world, and have sought advice from several respectable Buddhist masters. I think he's a bit naive, perhaps because he didn't get much education, but nevertheless he strives to do what he believes to be morally right. 

Based on these, I have quite enough information to predict whether the two would be willing to collaborate. And it is well within my rights to share my conclusion. Everyone is of course free to agree or disagree with me. 

By the way, another reason why they are unlikely to work together is because the martial arts circle in China does not consider Jackie Chen a martial artist, as he never trained in a martial arts school. This is why he was not in Jack Ma's stupid short film Gong Shou Dao. All performers in that film were invited by Jet Li and worked pro bono to promote martial arts.

author: @rammehta3056
Movie Name: Shang-Chi and the Legend of the Ten Rings

Comment:
I wasn't that impress with the movie though.  I guess everyone have their own taste.  Was it a good movie?  Sure.  Was it spectacular? No.  Does it blow your mind? No.  Does it have good fight scenes, sure.  Does the fights blow your mind?  No.  Does it have CGI? Yes.  Does it look corny with some CGI? Yes.  Does the acting look good? Sure.  Is the story compelling? No.  Does the fighting in the scaffle remind you one of Jackie Chan's fight scenes? Yes.  Is it a typical Hollywood CGI monster Harry Potter type movie? Yes.  Is it an Asian superhero movie made to appeal more to the West than the East?  Yes.  Is it a movie that I will watch on repeat?  No.  Will I watch the sequel?  Maybe.  Is the superhero look appealing? Sure.  Is Aquafina annoying?  No.  Is the dragon fight scenes in the end appealing? No.  Is Tony Leung's acting spectacular? Yes.  Is the music dope?  Yes.  Will you recommend this movie to an Asian friend? No.  Will you recommend this movie to a white friend?  Yes. 

Score:  B-

I decided to watch it today even if I knew that it would be just somewhat boring movie. I am 26min in and it's just a mess. Then we reach the part of MC backstory and well you see his mother died but his father trained him like a assassin since he was 5 years old or something. His sister wasn't trained but she is a genius of geniuses so she picked up all of this skills by just watching.
I watched movies like Kill Bill, Blade, Jackie Chans movies and etc. This is not about race or something. I love fun movies and I don't really who is in a main role. Out of many movie I saw this one has a weird beginning. In the trailer you see MC training and going trough some harsh stuff too. Sister is in the background training by herself and becoming more overpowered :D
